MSQE CAPSTONE: Project Summary & Results

Andrew Frohner

2025-08-24

Executive Summary

This capstone project examines the modeling and forecasting of a U.S. equity portfolio sorted by firm size, value, and profitability characteristics, using advanced econometric techniques and a robust blend of academic theory and empirical methods. The analysis focuses on the excess return of a small-cap, value-oriented, and high-profitability stock portfolio, benchmarked above the risk-free rate, and explores how this return is influenced by macroeconomic forces, market risk, credit conditions, and volatility dynamics.

Project Motivation

The study is grounded in the challenge faced by individual and institutional investors: how to optimize long-run returns while managing risk, especially in environments where risk-free assets do not preserve purchasing power over time. The research is motivated by the need to provide actionable insights for retirement planning, portfolio management, and understanding the drivers of equity returns beyond traditional models.

Methodological Approach

The project rigorously reviews foundational asset pricing theories, including the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), Arbitrage Pricing Theory (APT), and the Fama-French multifactor frameworks. It evaluates the limitations of these models and incorporates more recent advances by integrating macroeconomic and structural factors, such as credit spreads, monetary policy variables, and market volatility (VIX).

A unique dataset is constructed, combining portfolio-level returns (sourced from the Kenneth French Data Library) with a comprehensive set of macroeconomic indicators and exogenous shocks (from FRED and other sources). The analysis applies a series of statistical tests ahead of model construction to account for issues commonly found in time-series data.

Modeling and Forecasting Results

Multiple modeling strategies are employed:

Structural Equation Modeling: Linking portfolio pricing to key drivers such as the investment factor (CMA), credit spreads, money supply growth, and implied volatility.

Volatility Modeling: Employing GARCH and ARCH-In mean models to validate the choice of structural volatility over inertial in the MEM.

Vector Autoregression: This provides an alternative framework for forecasting time series data. It is less restrictive than a structural model because it does not impose theoretical relationships between the endogenous variables. The structure of the VAR can take multiple forms. Decisions made about the lag length and estimation technique can impact the forecast result. Incorporating a long lag series in a VAR can capture persistent relationships in a time series and reduce autocorrelation in residuals, but it also adds estimated coefficients (estimation error).

ARIMA: Used to gauge the dependent variables’ sensitivity to its historical values. Another desirable feature of the univariate inertial modeling technique is that typically (not always) they are more parsimonious than a structural model. Resulting in a forecast build with less estimation error.

Forecasting Techniques

Methods based: Each individual modeling method (Structural MEM, Vectorautoregression, Bayesian Vectorautoregression, and ARIMA) was used to produce a forecast for the portfolio PRICE.

Combination Forecasting: Four difference combination forecasts were generated using equal and optimal weighting strategies

Key findings include:

The analyzed portfolio produces historically attractive excess returns but exhibits marked volatility and negative skewness, emphasizing drawdown risk.

Macroeconomic variables like credit spreads and monetary conditions, as well as exogenous shocks (e.g., financial crises), exert substantial influence over returns.

The structural multi-equation model, while not always the most accurate in forecast error terms, best replicates the true volatility dynamics of the selected portfolio.

Forecast combination approaches, weighted by in-sample performance, yield enhanced accuracy over singular, methods-based forecast techniques.

Implications and Takeaways

This study demonstrates that integrating economic theory with comprehensive data and modern econometric modeling yields a richer understanding of equity portfolio behavior, especially under stress scenarios. Key recommendations include:

Portfolio managers should consider multi-factor models that incorporate macro-financial variables, not just firm characteristics, to set return expectations and manage risks.

Scenario-based forecasting, incorporating both baseline and crisis conditions, provides investors with better tools for strategic planning and risk management.

Forecast combination techniques outperform any single modeling approach and should be standard in risk and asset allocation analysis.

The structural model’s alignment with real-world volatility underscores the importance of representing “fat tails” and extreme moves often observed in equity returns.

Overall, the capstone provides a holistic framework for understanding, modeling, and forecasting the returns of a size, value, and profitability-sorted equity portfolio amid the evolving realities of U.S. financial markets.

Forecasting the model’s exogenous variables provides the endogenous variable set a non-arbitrary “reality” to live in. Exogenous variables in this model were forecasted using univariate inertial techniques with long lag structures. This forecasting methodology ensures that the exogenous variables take on a path that is absent of unusual or unanticipated shocks while simultaneously capturing realized historical patterns in the data. The exceptionally long lags were required for producing forecasts that contained some level of volatility.

Vector Autoregression is another form of simultaneous estimation that we can use to estimate a set of endogenous variables. This provides an alternative framework for forecasting time series data. It is less restrictive than a structural model because it does not impose theoretical relationships between the endogenous variables. The structure of the VAR can take multiple forms. Decisions made about the lag length and estimation technique can impact the forecast result. Incorporating a long lag series in a VAR can capture persistent relationships in a time series and reduce autocorrelation in residuals, but it also adds estimated coefficients (estimation error). A highly parameterized model will also be more sensitive to individual data points and is prone to picking up the data’s “noise.”

Optimal Weighting Methodology

Optimal Weight #1 – Measured each individual forecast methods contribution to the overall squared error of the forecast. Initially it assigned an equal (25%) weight to each technique. Any individual technique that contributed > 25% of the overall share of the squared error was downweighted, and techniques will <25% of the error share were upweighted.

Resulting Forecast Weights:

\[ \text{PRICE}_t = 0.254\, (\text{PRICE_MEM}_t) + 0.064\, (\text{PRICE_VAR1}_t) + 0.264\, (\text{PRICE_BVAR}_t) + 0.388\, (\text{PRICE_ARIMA}_t) \]

Optimal Weight #2 – Regressed the historical values of Price on the each of the four forecasts of price (Structural, VAR 1 , BVAR, ARIMA) and used their estimated slope coefficients as the forecast weight. Normalization was applied to the coefficient estimates so that the slope coefficients from the regression added up to 1 (i.e. 100% weight allocation). Unlike equal-weight or the Optimal Weight 1, this technique permits negative weights to be assigned to forecast techniques. The regression model for this optimal weight forecast took the following form:

\[ \text{PRICE}_t = -1 + \beta_1\, \text{PRICE_MEM}_t + \beta_2\, \text{PRICE_VAR1}_t + \beta_1\, \text{PRICE_BVAR}_t + \beta_1\, \text{PRICE_ARIMA}_t + \varepsilon_t \]

Resulting Forecast Weights:

\[ \text{PRICE}_t = 0.208\, (\text{PRICE_MEM}_t) + 0.327\, (\text{PRICE_VAR1}_t) - 0.387\, (\text{PRICE_BVAR}_t) + 0.851\, (\text{PRICE_ARIMA}_t) \]

The estimated Betas from this regression are the coefficients that minimize the sum of the squared errors between the actual value and the forecasted value. Resulting Forecast:

\[ \text{PRICE}_t = 0.01\, (\text{PRICE_MEM}_t) + 0.094\, (\text{PRICE_VAR1}_t) + 0.01\, (\text{PRICE_BVAR}_t) + 0.886\, (\text{PRICE_ARIMA}_t) \]

Optimal Weight #3 – Initially assigned equal-weights to the individual forecasts and applied a constrained optimization to minimize the combination forecast MAPE. The constraint mandated that no individual technique could receive less than a 1% weight allocation to the combination.

Resulting Forecast Weights:

\[ \text{PRICE}_t = 0.01\, (\text{PRICE_MEM}_t) + 0.094\, (\text{PRICE_VAR1}_t) + 0.01\, (\text{PRICE_BVAR}_t) + 0.886\, (\text{PRICE_ARIMA}_t) \]

Optimal weighting methods #2 and #3 result in a high chance for one of the individual techniques to receive a dominant weighting allocation.
